%I A395979 #24 May 19 2026 19:06:03
%S A395979 3,5,7,23041,446960641,3208642561,912680550401,1825696645121,
%T A395979 3580135407617
%N A395979 Ultra-elite primes: elite primes p such that all their Fermat remainders are either primitive roots, or all nonprimitive roots, modulo p.
%C A395979 5*2^26607 + 1 is the smallest prime of the form 5*2^k + 1 that belongs to this sequence.
%C A395979 Are there any terms p > 5 such that p - 1 is not divisible by any prime divisor of a Fermat number?
%H A395979 Amin Witno, <a href="https://doi.org/10.1285/i15900932v30n1p133">Primes modulo which almost all Fermat numbers are primitive roots</a>, Note Mat. 30 (2010) n. 1, 133-140.
%e A395979 The prime number 23041 provides four Fermat remainders (9692, 366, 18021, and 3588) each being a quadratic non-residue modulo p, i.e., 23041 is an elite prime. Since all its Fermat remainders are primitive roots (no Fermat remainder is a nonprimitive root), 23041 is in the sequence.
%o A395979 (Magma) // Append terms from A102742 to list Elite;
%o A395979 Elite:=[];
%o A395979 lst:=[]; MO:=func<p | Modorder(2, p)>; PD:=func<p | PrimeDivisors(p-1)>; for a in [1..#Elite] do p:=Elite[a]; firstm:=Valuation(MO(p), 2); shift:=MO(p) div 2^firstm; if shift eq 1 then Append(~lst, p); else lastm:=firstm+MO(shift)-1; residues:=[]; for m in [firstm..lastm] do Append(~residues, Modexp(2, 2^m, p)+1); end for; nPD:=#PD(p); nresidues:=#residues; temp1:=[]; for k in [1..nresidues] do for j in [2..nPD] do d:=Truncate((p-1)/PD(p)[j]); Append(~temp1, Modexp(residues[k], d, p)); end for; end for; temp2:=[]; for k in [1..nresidues] do x:=&*[temp1[j]-1: j in [(k-1)*(nPD-1)+1..k*(nPD-1)]]; if IsZero(x) then Append(~temp2, 0); else Append(~temp2, 1); end if; end for; s:=&+[temp2[b]: b in [1..nresidues]]; if IsZero(s) or s eq nresidues then Append(~lst, p); end if; end if; end for; lst;
%Y A395979 Cf. A102742, A346542.
%K A395979 nonn,more
%O A395979 1,1
%A A395979 _Arkadiusz Wesolowski_, May 12 2026
